:"1208","1200":"1200","1231":"1231","1185":"1185","1184":"1184","1208":"1208","1207":"1207","Toledo, Castilla-La Mancha, España":"Toledo, Castilla-La Mancha, Spanien","Toledo, New Castile, Spain":"Diócesis de Toledo, Spanien","España":"Spanien"},"nl":{"1185–":"1185–Overleden","1184–1207":"1184–1207","1184–Male":"1184–Overleden","1208–1231":"1208–1231","1185–Female":"1185–Overleden","Cir 1208":"1208","1200":"1200","1231":"1231","1185":"1185","1184":"1184","1208":"1208","1207":"1207","Toledo, Castilla-La Mancha, España":"Toledo, Castilla-La Mancha, Spanje","Toledo, New Castile, Spain":"Diócesis de Toledo, Spanje","España":"Spanje"},"en":{"1185–":"1185–Deceased","1184–1207":"1184–1207","1184–Male":"1184–Deceased","1208–1231":"1208–1231","1185–Female":"1185–Deceased","Cir 1208":"1208","1200":"1200","1231":"1231","1185":"1185","1184":"1184","1208":"1208","1207":"1207","Toledo, Castilla-La Mancha, España":"Toledo, Castilla-La Mancha, Spain","Toledo, New Castile, Spain":"Diócesis de Toledo, Spain","España":"Spain","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Dominico","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English and German: from a vernacular form of the Late Latin personal name <i>Dominicus</i>, from Latin <i>dominicus</i> ‘of the Lord’, an adjectival derivative of <i>dominus</i> ‘lord, master’. This was borne by a Spanish saint (1170–1221) who founded the Dominican order of friars and whose fame added greatly to the popularity of the name (<i>Domingo</i> in Spanish), already established because of its symbolic value. In medieval England it may have been used as a personal name for a child born on a Sunday, though as an English surname it is comparatively rare. In North America, the English form of the surname has absorbed cognates from other languages, especially Italian   Domenico   (see also 2 below). See also   Domingo  , compare   Dominic  .","Americanized form of German, Polish, Czech, Slovak, Slovenian, and Croatian   Dominik   and of Croatian <b>Dominić</b> (see   Dominic  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Domina","meanings":["Italian (Sicily): from the female personal name <i>Domina</i>, from Latin <i>domina</i> ‘mistress (of the house)’.","Polish: from a short form of the personal name <i>Dominik</i>, Late Latin <i>Dominicus</i> (see   Dominick  ).","Russian and Ukrainian: feminine form (denoting ‘the daughter, or wife of’) of   Domin  ."]},{"name":"Dominic","meanings":["English (Nottinghamshire): from the personal name <i>Dominic</i> (see   Dominick  ). In North America, the English form of the surname has absorbed cognates from other languages, especially Italian   Domenico  .","Croatian (<b>Dominić</b>): patronymic from the personal name   Domin  , a short form of   Dominik  ."]},{"name":"Dominiak","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Polish Casimir, Krzysztof, Ludwik, Zbigniew.","Polish: patronymic from the personal name <i>Dominik</i>, from Late Latin <i>Dominicus</i> (see   Dominick  )."]},{"name":"Domenech","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Luis, Guillermo, Jose, Armando, Angel, Carlos, Enrique, Fernando, Juan, Manuel, Orlando, Sergio.","Catalan (<b>Domènech</b>): from the personal name <i>Domènec</i>, Catalan form of   Dominick  ."]},{"name":"Dominik","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Otto, Florian, Guenter, Jurgen, Kurt.  Polish Danuta, Janusz, Tadeusz.","German, Polish, Czech, Slovak, Slovenian, and Croatian: from the personal name <i>Dominik</i>, Late Latin <i>Dominicus</i> (see   Dominick  )."]},{"name":"Domenico","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Angelo, Alfonse, Concetta, Dante, Dino, Palma.","Italian: from the personal name <i>Domenico</i>, from Late Latin <i>Dominicus</i> (see   Dominick  )."]},{"name":"Domingo","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Manuel, Juan, Ernesto, Rolando, Violeta, Virgilio, Carlos, Fernando, Francisco, Jaime, Jesus.  Italian Antonio, Quirino, Dante, Federico, Jovencio, Lorenzo, Romeo, Salvatore, Carmelo, Caesar, Enrico, Franco.","Spanish and Italian (Sicily; of Spanish origin): from a vernacular form of the Late Latin personal name <i>Dominicus</i> (see   Dominick  ). This surname is also found in southern France.","History: The surname Domingo is found in Quebec City by 1681, brought from Bayonne in France by Étienne Domingo who, however, apparently had no male descendants."]},{"name":"Dominique","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French/Haitian Alain, Alcide, Andre, Angelle, Antoine, Brunel, Edele, Jean Baptiste, Jean Marc, Jean Robert, Jean-Claude, Jeanne Marie.","French and West Indian (mainly Haiti): from the French personal name <i>Dominique</i>, from Late Latin <i>Dominicus</i> (see   Dominick  ).","History: This surname is listed in the register of Huguenot ancestors recognized by the Huguenot Society of America."]},{"name":"Domonkos","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Hungarian Arpad, Istvan.","Hungarian: from the personal names <i>Domokos</i> or<i>Domonkos</i>, Hungarian equivalents of   Dominick  ."]},{"name":"Deda","meanings":["Albanian: from the personal name <i>Dedë</i> (definite form <i>Deda</i>), an old vernacular short form of <i>Domenik</i> (see   Dominick  )."]}]},{"name":"Maria","type":"FIRST","meanings":["A name derived from Mapia, one of the Greek forms of Miriam. Maria is found as a male name as well as a female name. Viscount Montague, of Cowdray, Sussex, who succeeded to the title as second viscount, was christened Anthony Maria Browne. In Camden's Remains (p. 44), referred to in Delicie Literarise, occurs Thomas Maria Wingfield; and there was also a Sir Edward Maria Wingfield. The name appears to have been adopted in the latter family from Mary, daughter of Henry VIII. Compare Notes and Queries 5th S. ii. 73, 316, 478. Marie is frequently found as a male name in France and in other parts of the Continent."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1354684,"age":15,"year":"1200","julianDay":2159351,"description":"The Christian territory controlled the Kingdoms of Aragon, Navarre, and Castile.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Maria Dominico was born in 1185, in Toledo, Castilla-La Mancha, Spain. She had at least 1 son with Pedro Garcia. She died in Spain."},"et":{"1185–":"1185–Surnud","1184–1207":"1184–1207","1184–Male":"1184–Surnud","1208–1231":"1208–1231","1185–Female":"1185–Surnud","Cir 1208":"1208","1200":"1200","1231":"1231","1185":"1185","1184":"1184","1208":"1208","1207":"1207","Toledo, Castilla-La Mancha, España":"Toledo, Castilla-La Mancha, Hispaania","Toledo, New Castile, Spain":"Diócesis de Toledo, Hispaania","España":"Hispaania"},"fi":{"1185–":"1185–Kuollut","1184–1207":"1184–1207","1184–Male":"1184–Kuollut","1208–1231":"1208–1231","1185–Female":"1185–Kuollut","Cir 1208":"1208","1200":"1200","1231":"1231","1185":"1185","1184":"1184","1208":"1208","1207":"1207","Toledo, Castilla-La Mancha, España":"Toledo, Castilla-La Mancha, Espanja","Toledo, New Castile, Spain":"Diócesis de Toledo, Espanja","España":"Espanja"},"fr":{"1185–":"1185–Décédée","1184–1207":"1184–1207","1184–Male":"1184–Décédé","1208–1231":"1208–1231","1185–Female":"1185–Décédée","Cir 1208":"1208","1200":"1200","1231":"1231","1185":"1185","1184":"1184","1208":"1208","1207":"1207","Toledo, Castilla-La Mancha, España":"Toledo, Castilla-La Mancha, Espagne","Toledo, New Castile, Spain":"Diócesis de Toledo, Espagne","España":"Espagne","lifeSummary":"Maria Dominico est née en 1185, à Toledo, Castilla-La Mancha, Espagne. Elle a eu au moins 1 fils avec Pedro Garcia. Elle est décédée à Espagne."},"de":{"1185–":"1185–Verstorben","1184–1207":"1184–1207","1184–Male":"1184–Verstorben","1208–1231":"1208–1231","1185–Female":"1185–Verstorben","Cir 1208":"1208","1200":"1200","1231":"1231","1185":"1185","1184":"1184","1208":"1208","1207":"1207","Toledo, Castilla-La Mancha, España":"Toledo, Castilla-La Mancha, Spanien","Toledo, New Castile, Spain":"Diócesis de Toledo, Spanien"